10 An Act relating to officers; amending 51 O.S. 2021,
Section 50, which relates to the Personal Privacy
11 Protection Act; adding certain exceptions to
authorize disclosure of personal affiliation
12 information; requiring certain notice; updating
statutory language; updating statutory references;
13 and providing an effective date.
14
15
16 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
17 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 51 O.S. 2021, Section 50, is
18 amended to read as follows:
19 Section 50. A. This act shall be known and may be cited as the
20 “Personal Privacy Protection Act”.
21 B. As used in the Personal Privacy Protection Act:
22 1. “Personal affiliation information” means any list, record,
23 register, registry, roll, roster, or other compilation of data of
24 any kind that directly or indirectly identifies a person as a
Req. No. 3837 Page 1

1 memb er, supporter, or volunteer of, or donor of financial or
2 nonfinancial support to, any entity organized pursuant to Section
3 501(c) of the United States Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as
4 amended; and
5 2. “Public agency” means any state or local governmental unit,
6 however designated, including, but not limited to, the State of
7 Oklahoma this state; any department, agency, office, commission,
8 board, division, or other entity of the State of Oklahoma this
9 state, including those created or established pursuant to
10 constitutional provisions; any political subdivision of the State of
11 Oklahoma, this state including, but not limited to, a county, city,
12 township, village, school district, community college district, or
13 any other local governmental unit, agency, authority, council,
14 board, or commission; or any state or local court, tribunal, or
15 other judicial or quasi-judicial body.
16 C. A public agency shall not do any of the following:
17 1. Require any individual to provide the public agency with
18 personal affiliation information or otherwise compel the release of
19 personal affiliation information;
20 2. Require any entity organized pursuant to Section 501(c) of
21 the United States Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended, to
22 provide the state agency or political subdivision with personal
23 affiliation information or otherwise compel the release of personal
24 affiliation information;
Req. No. 3837 Page 2

1 3. Release, publicize, or otherwise publicly disclose any
2 personal affiliation information in the possession of the public
3 agency; or
4 4. Request or require a current or prospective contractor or
5 grantee with the public agency to provide the public agency with a
6 list of entities organized pursuant to Section 501(c) of the United
7 States Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended, to which it has
8 provided financial or nonfinancial support.
9 D. Personal affiliation information is shall be exempt from the
10 disclosure requirements of the Oklahoma Open Records Act.
11 E. The Personal Privacy Protection Act shall not preclude any
12 of the following:
13 1. Any report or disclosure required by the Oklahoma Ethics
14 Commission prior to the effective date of this act November 1, 2020;
15 2. Any lawful warrant for personal affiliation information
16 issued by a court of competent jurisdiction;
17 3. Any A lawful request by the Attorney General for information
18 pertaining to former and current members of the governing body of an
19 entity organized as a 501(c)(3) entity pursuant to a review,
20 examination, or investigation authorized by Section 552.14a or
21 552.24 of Title 18 of the Oklahoma Statutes, or Section 175.18,
22 175.706, 300.16, 602, or 1608.12 of Title 60 of the Oklahoma
23 Statutes. When the Attorney General requests board member
24 information through the issuance of a lawful civil investigative
Req. No. 3837 Page 3

1 dema nd, such demand shall notify the 501(c)(3) entity that it has
2 the right to file a petition to modify or set aside the demand in
3 the district court of the county where the entity has its principal
4 place of business or in the district court of Oklahoma County;
5 4. Disclosure by the Attorney General of information pertaining
6 to former and current board members of the governing body of an
7 entity organized as a 501(c)(3) entity in court pleadings and
8 motions or as relevant evidence related to a civil or criminal
9 action;
10 5. A lawful request for discovery of personal affiliation
11 information in litigation if both of the following conditions are
12 met:
13 a. the requester demonstrates a compelling need for the
14 personal affiliation information requested by clear
15 and convincing evidence, and
16 b. the requester obtains a protective order barring
17 disclosure of personal affiliation information to any
18 person not directly involved in the litigation; or
19 4. Admission 6. Except as otherwise provided in this section,
20 admission of personal affiliation information as relevant evidence
21 before a court of competent jurisdiction. However, no court shall
22 publicly reveal disclose personal affiliation information absent a
23 specific finding of good cause; or
24
Req. No. 3837 Page 4

1 7. A lawful request for, or disclosure of, personal affiliation
2 information that is publicly or voluntarily disclosed by the person
3 or entity to which it relates.
4 F. Any person alleging a violation of the Personal Privacy
5 Protection Act may bring a civil action for appropriate injunctive
6 relief, damages, or both injunctive relief and damages. Damages
7 awarded pursuant to this section may include one of the following,
8 as appropriate:
9 1. A sum of money not less than Two Thousand Five Hundred
10 Dollars ($2,500.00) to compensate for injury or loss caused by each
11 violation of this act the Personal Privacy Protection Act; or
12 2. For an intentional violation of this act the Personal
13 Privacy Protection Act, a sum of money not to exceed three times the
14 sum described in paragraph 1 of this subsection.
15 G. A court, in rendering judgment in an action brought pursuant
16 to this section, may award all or a portion of the costs of
17 litigation, including reasonable attorney fees and witness fees, to
18 the complainant in the action if the court determines that the award
19 is appropriate.
20 H. A person who knowingly violates this act the Personal
21 Privacy Protection Act shall, upon conviction, be guilty of a
22 misdemeanor punishable by a fine not to exceed One Thousand Dollars
23 ($1,000.00), by imprisonment in the county jail for not more than
24
Req. No. 3837 Page 5

1 nine ty (90) days or a fine of not more than One Thousand Dollars
2 ($1,000.00), or by both such fine and imprisonment.
3 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
